{{Infobox Film Festival | name = Crazy8s | logo = | image = Crazy8s_Logo.jpg | number = fewest, 3 (1999); most, 8 (2006, 2008) | location = [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]] | founded = 1999 | website = {{url|http://crazy8s.film}} }}
'''Crazy8s''' is a filmmaking competition and festival held annually in [[Vancouver, BC, Canada]]. It provides funding and support to local filmmakers to shoot and edit a short film in eight days.<ref name="Sweet16">{{cite web|last1=Fleming|first1=Andrew|date=1 March 2015|title=Crazy 8s turn sweet 16|url=http://www.vancourier.com/opinion/crazy-8s-turn-sweet-16-1.2179673|publisher=[[Vancouver Courier]]|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref>
Notable past participants include [[Kaare Andrews]], [[Samm Barnes]], [[Carl Bessai]], [[James Dunnison]], [[Mackenzie Gray]], Matthew Kowalchuk, [[CJ Wallis]], [[Zach Lipovsky]], [[Elan Mastai]], [[Camille Mitchell]], Nimisha Mukerji, [[Graham Wardle]] and [[Kyra Zagorsky]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mack|first1=Adrian|date=24 February 2016|title=Bedlam with benefits is the key to Crazy8s|url=https://www.straight.com/movies/645501/bedlam-benefits-key-crazy8s|publisher=[[The Georgia Straight]]|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref> It has been called one of the best platforms for emerging filmmakers in Vancouver.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Javier|first1=Carlo|date=22 February 2016|title=Eight crazy days|url=http://www.capilanocourier.com/arts-culture/eight-crazy-days/|publisher=[[The Capilano Courier]]|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref>
==History== Crazy8s was founded in 1999 by Andrew Williamson.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Georgian|first1=Francis|title=Crazy8s Film Festival celebrates 15 Years|url=http://www.vancouversun.com/videos/local/video.html?embedCode=llY2pyazrjEAAAG-vLrQwUnRFxYjQuTd&__lsa=59d8-cc9e|publisher=The Vancouver Sun|accessdate=6 March 2016}}</ref> Teams of filmmakers pitch their concepts to industry professionals. After fine-tuning their concepts and delivering revised scripts, 6 winners are chosen to receive $1,000 and a production package and have three days to shoot followed by five days of post-production.<ref name="Ubyssey">{{cite web|last1=Tejeida|first1=Aurora|date=27 February 2014|title=Crazy8s film fest gives students eight days to produce a masterpiece|url=http://ubyssey.ca/culture/crazy8s-film-fest-398/|publisher=[[The Ubyssey]]|accessdate=6 March 2016|ref=Ubyssey}}</ref> Most of the approximately 2,000 people involved are industry professionals.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Uitto|first1=Justin|title=Crazy 8s: Filmmaking on a budget|date=31 March 2015|url=http://beatroute.ca/2015/03/31/crazy-8s-filmmaking-on-a-budget/|website=[[BeatRoute Magazine]]|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref>
Dylan Akio Smith's ''Man. Feel. Pain.'' won Best Canadian Short Film at the [[2004 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Past Award Winners: Short Cuts Award for Best Canadian Film|url=http://tiff.net/festivals/festival15/past-award-winners/|website=tiff.net|publisher=Toronto International Film Festival|accessdate=28 March 2016}}</ref> Zach Lipovsky's ''Crazy Late'' is credited with helping earn him a spot on the reality show ''[[On the Lot]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Video: Crazy 8s juror Zach Lipovsky|date=11 February 2015|url=http://www.vancouversun.com/entertainment/movie-guide/Video+Crazy+juror+Zach+Lipovsky/10805465/story.html|publisher=[[The Vancouver Sun]]|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref> ''Earthlickers'' and ''Bed Bugs: A Musical Love Story'' later screened at the 2014 [[Whistler Film Festival]].<ref name="Sweet16" />
Joel Ashton McCarthy's ''I Love You So Much It's Killing Them'' won Best Short Film at [[Bruce Campbell]]'s third annual GroovyFest.<ref>{{cite web|last1=IP|first1=STEPHANIE|title=Vancouver-shot short film earns nod from cult horror icon Bruce Campbell|url=http://vancouversun.com/entertainment/local-arts/vancouver-shot-short-film-earns-nod-from-cult-horror-icon-bruce-campbell|publisher=The Vancouver Sun|accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref>
==Galas== The finished films are screened at a Gala Screening followed by an afterparty.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jones|first1=Scott|title=Crazy8s Challenges Filmmakers To Work Under Pressure|url=http://epn.tv/all/spotlight/crazy-8s-challenges-filmmakers-to-work-under-pressure/|website=epn.tv|publisher=epn|accessdate=13 March 2016}}</ref> The 2010 gala was held March 27 at the [[Vogue Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Myara|first1=Shana|title=Female filmmakers take Crazy8s dare|date=24 March 2010|url=https://www.straight.com/article-299453/vancouver/women-take-crazy8s-dare|publisher=The Georgia Straight|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref> The 2014 competition attracted 154 applicants.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Schaefer|first1=Glen|title=Bedbugs, time travel, a deal with God and a sexy apocalypse among Crazy8s winners|date=14 January 2014|url=http://blogs.theprovince.com/2014/01/14/bedbugs-time-travel-a-deal-with-god-and-a-sexy-apocalypse-among-crazy8s-winners/|publisher=The Province|accessdate=6 March 2016}}</ref> The 2015 gala screening was held February 28 at The Centre For Performing Arts and had 196 applicants.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Atkinson|first1=Cathryn|date=26 February 2016|title=Crazy8s filmmaking is no drag for director Angie Nolan|url=http://www.piquenewsmagazine.com/whistler/crazy8s-filmmaking-is-no-drag-for-director-angie-nolan/Content?oid=2640798|publisher=Pique News Magazine|accessdate=6 March 2016}}</ref> It was hosted by [[Diana Bang]], attracted 1,700 people and featured the band [[No Sinner]] at the afterparty.<ref name="Sweet16" /> The 2016 gala screening was held February 27 at The Centre For Performing Arts and was hosted by [[Ellie Harvie]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Conner|first1=Shawn|date=24 February 2016|title=Romance, dystopian sci-fi and grocery store action – it's all part of this year's Crazy8s short film showcase!|url=http://www.insidevancouver.ca/2016/02/24/crazy8s-gala-and-afterparty-2016/|publisher=Inside Vancouver|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref> The 2017 competition attracted 216 teams and will screen the final six films February 25 at The Centre For Performing Arts with an official afterparty at [[Science World (Vancouver)|Science World]].<ref>{{cite web|title=UPDATE: Filmmakers pick Langley as backdrop for shorts|url=http://www.langleyadvance.com/entertainment/411804426.html|website=Langley Advance|publisher=www.langleyadvance.com|accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref>
